# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diamond-model-intrusion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] An **advanced persistent threat** (**APT**) is a stealthy cybersecurity threat, typically manipulated by a state or state-sponsored group, which gains unauthorized access to a computer network and remains undetected for an extended period.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] In recent times, the term may also refer to non-state-sponsored groups conducting large-scale targeted intrusions for specific goals.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Such threat actors' motivations are typically political or economic.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Every major business sector has recorded instances of cyberattacks by advanced actors with specific goals, whether to steal, spy, or disrupt.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] These targeted sectors include government, defense, financial services, legal services, industrial, telecoms, consumer goods and many more.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Some groups utilize traditional espionage vectors, including social engineering, human intelligence and infiltration to gain access to a physical location to enable network attacks.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] The purpose of these attacks is to install custom malware.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] APT attacks on mobile devices have also become a legitimate concern, since attackers are able to penetrate into cloud and mobile infrastructure to eavesdrop, steal, and tamper with data.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] The median "dwell-time", the time an APT attack goes undetected, differs widely between regions.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] FireEye reported the mean dwell-time for 2018 in the Americas as 71 days, EMEA as 177 days, and APAC as 204 days.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Such a long dwell-time allows attackers a significant amount of time to go through the attack cycle, propagate, and achieve their objectives.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Warnings against targeted, socially-engineered emails dropping trojans to exfiltrate sensitive information were published by UK and US CERT organisations in 2005.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] This method was used throughout the early 1990s and does not in itself constitute an APT.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] The term "advanced persistent threat" has been cited as originating from the United States Air Force in 2006 with Colonel Greg Rattray cited as the individual who coined the term.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] The Stuxnet computer worm, which targeted the computer hardware of Iran's nuclear program, is one example of an APT attack.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] In this case, the Iranian government might consider the Stuxnet creators to be an advanced persistent threat.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Advanced persistent threat (APT) as a term may be shifting focus to computer-based hacking due to the rising number of occurrences.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] PC World reported an 81 percent increase from 2010 to 2011 of particularly advanced targeted computer attacks.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Actors in many countries have used cyberspace as a means to gather intelligence on individuals and groups of individuals of interest.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] The United States Cyber Command is tasked with coordinating the US military's offensive and defensive cyber operations.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Numerous sources have alleged that some APT groups are affiliated with, or are agents of, governments of sovereign states.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] A Bell Canada study provided deep research into the anatomy of APTs and uncovered widespread presence in Canadian government and critical infrastructure.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Attribution was established to Chinese and Russian actors.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] In incidents analysed by Mandiant, the average period over which the attackers controlled the victim's network was one year, with longest – almost five years.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] The infiltrations were allegedly performed by Shanghai-based Unit 61398 of People's Liberation Army.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Chinese officials have denied any involvement in these attacks.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Previous reports from Secdev had previously discovered and implicated Chinese actors.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] There are tens of millions of malware variations, which makes it extremely challenging to protect organizations from APT.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] While APT activities are stealthy and hard to detect, the command and control network traffic associated with APT can be detected at the network layer level with sophisticated methods.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Deep log analyses and log correlation from various sources is of limited usefulness in detecting APT activities.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] It is challenging to separate noises from legitimate traffic.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Traditional security technology and methods have been ineffective in detecting or mitigating APTs.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Active cyber defense has yielded greater efficacy in detecting and prosecuting APTs (find, fix, finish) when applying cyber threat intelligence to hunt and adversary pursuit activities.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Human-Introduced Cyber Vulnerabilities (HICV) are a weak cyber link that are neither well understood nor mitigated, constituting a significant attack vector.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Multiple organizations may assign different names to the same actor.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] As separate researchers could each have their own varying assessments of an APT group, companies such as CrowdStrike, Kaspersky, Mandiant, and Microsoft, among others, have their own internal naming schemes.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Names between different organizations may refer to overlapping but ultimately different groups, based on various data gathered.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] CrowdStrike assigns animals by nation-state or other category, such as "Kitten" for Iran and "Spider" for groups focused on cybercrime.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies have named groups based on this system — Rampant Kitten, for instance, was named by Check Point rather than CrowdStrike.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Dragos bases its names for APT groups on minerals.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Mandiant assigns numbered acronyms in three categories, APT, FIN, and UNC, resulting in APT names like FIN7.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies using a similar system include Proofpoint (TA) and IBM (ITG and Hive).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] Microsoft used to assign names from the periodic table, often stylized in all-caps (e.g.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/advanced-persistent-threat] POTASSIUM); in April 2023, Microsoft changed its naming schema to use weather-based names (e.g.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Sources of cyber threat intelligence include open-source data, social media, operational and technical intelligence, device log files, forensic analysis, internet traffic, as well as data from the dark web and deep web.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Modern CTI programs stand out from just using raw security data because they combine technical monitoring, outside intelligence sources, and analysis methods to prepare specific and useful assessments about cyber threats aimed at particular organizations or business sectors.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Analytical interpretation gives context to attackers’ actions, capabilities, and intentions, helping organizations set priorities and allocate security resources effectively.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] When companies base decisions on intelligence and analysis, they can act proactively instead of just reacting to security incidents, stopping breaches before they happen.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] This approach has become increasingly important in recent years, as IBM estimates that exploiting vulnerabilities is the most common way companies are breached, making up 47% of all attacks.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The COVID-19 pandemic and the rise in remote work have also contributed to increased vulnerability to threats, making corporate data more exposed.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Due to growing threats on the one hand, and increasing analytical demands on the other, many companies have decided in recent years to outsource their threat analytics tasks to a managed security service provider (MSSP).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Cyber threat analytics has also become an important component of modern Security Operations Centers (SOCs), where threat intelligence data is used to enrich alerts, identify malicious infrastructure, and support incident response and threat hunting activities.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] There are three categorical levels of cyber threat intelligence: tactical, operational, and strategic.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Each serves a distinct audience and purpose in building a comprehensive threat assessment.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Technical threat analysis focuses on machine-readable indicators of compromise (IoCs): malicious IP addresses, domain names, file hashes, and command-and-control (C2) servers or infrastructure.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] This enables automated detection and response.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] While the conventional distinction is between strategic, tactical, and operational analytics, some large organizations often define technical threat analytics as a separate (fourth) category essential for Security Operations Centers (SOCs).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some threat analytics platforms also distinguish between indicator-based analytics and behavior-based analytics.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Indicator-based analytics focuses on specific technical artifacts: malicious IP addresses, file hashes, etc.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Behavior-based analytics analyzes attackers’ tactics and techniques to detect threats that may change their infrastructure or indicators over time.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] To obtain effective analytical insights, it is necessary to combine data from internal security tools with external technical and strategic reports to gain a more comprehensive view of the threat landscape.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The process of developing cyber threat intelligence is a circular and continuous process, known as the intelligence cycle, which is composed of five phases, carried out by intelligence teams to provide to leadership relevant and convenient intelligence to reduce danger and uncertainty.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The five phases are: 1) planning and direction; 2) collection; 3) processing; 4) analysis; 5) dissemination.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] In planning and directing, the customer of the intelligence product requests intelligence on a specific topic or objective.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Then, once directed by the client, the second phase begins, collection, which involves accessing the raw information that will be required to produce the finished intelligence product.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Finally, the dissemination phase, in which the newly selected threat intelligence is sent to the various users for their use.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The intelligence cycle model in the field of cyber threat analysis is based on traditional intelligence methods used by military and government intelligence agencies, where structured analysis is employed to transform raw data into the insights needed for decision-making.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Cybersecurity researchers also highlight other factors for good threat intelligence, such as accuracy, completeness, timeliness, compatibility, and relevance to the environment where it will be used.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat analytics helps improve threat detection mechanisms by identifying attackers’ methods and behavioral patterns that are not yet detected by automated security monitoring systems.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Organizations often deploy specialized software known as threat intelligence platforms (TIPs) to aggregate, analyze, and distribute threat intelligence data.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat intelligence platforms gather data from both internal and external sources, including security system telemetry, open-source intelligence feeds, malware repositories, vulnerability databases, and reports from security vendors.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] By aggregating and correlating indicators of compromise (IoCs) like malicious IP addresses, domain names, file hashes, and command-and-control infrastructure, these platforms help security professionals better understand threat contexts and identify the most significant threats.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] TI platforms are commonly integrated with other cybersecurity systems.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Integrations with tools such as security information and event management (SIEM) systems, endpoint detection and response (EDR) solutions, and incident response platforms enable automated alert enrichment and faster investigation of security incidents.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat intelligence platforms also support threat hunting and incident response by organizing indicators and intelligence reports within searchable repositories, allowing analysts to correlate events and identify patterns associated with specific campaigns or threat actors.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some threat intelligence platforms use automated data pipelines and machine learning techniques to process large volumes of threat data and generate analytical insights for proactive cybersecurity strategies.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Modern programs for collecting and analyzing cyber threat intelligence rely on standardized formats that enable automated exchange between organizations and security tools, as well as the processing of analytical data.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] STIX (Structured Threat Information Expression) is a standardized language for representing analytical information about cyber threats in a machine-readable format, allowing analysts to describe attackers, campaigns, vulnerabilities, and indicators within a structured data model.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Trusted Automated Exchange of Intelligence Information (TAXII) is a protocol for supporting the automated exchange of threat intelligence data, typically used to transmit intelligence in STIX format.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) is widely used in the exchange of threat intelligence to determine how sensitive information is shared among members of trusted communities.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Analysts use structured analytical models to understand the behavior of attackers and implement defensive measures.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Cyber Kill Chain model, developed by Lockheed Martin, describes the stages of a cyberattack as a linear progression: reconnaissance, weaponization (preparation of attack tools), delivery, exploitation of vulnerabilities, installation, command and control, and actions on objectives.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] This framework helps defenders identify at which stage an attack can be disrupted.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Diamond Model of Intrusion Analysis examines the relationships between four core features of any intrusion event: the adversary, their capabilities (tools and techniques), the infrastructure they use (domains, IP addresses, email addresses), and the victim.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Using these relationships across multiple events, analysts can pivot between incidents, identify patterns, and attribute activity to specific threat actors or campaigns.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The MITRE ATT&CK framework is a knowledge base of adversary tactics and techniques based on real-world observations.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] It organizes attacker behavior into 14 tactics (the "why" of an action - initial access, persistence, privilege escalation, defense evasion, etc.), and hundreds of techniques (the "how" - specific methods used to achieve each tactic).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Unlike the linear Cyber Kill Chain, ATT&CK provides a detailed matrix of adversary behaviors that can occur in any order or simultaneously.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Security teams use ATT&CK to map threat intelligence to defensive controls, assess coverage gaps, conduct red team exercises, and build detections aligned with actual adversary tradecraft.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] It has become the de facto standard for describing and sharing operational threat intelligence.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The increasing volume and velocity of cyber threat data have led organizations to automate significant parts of the threat intelligence lifecycle, including data collection, processing, correlation, and distribution.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Automated threat intelligence systems typically ingest data from multiple sources, and then process and correlate this information to identify patterns of malicious activity.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Machine-readable standards and transport protocols (STIX and TAXII) are an important component of automated CTI systems.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Integration between threat intelligence platforms and security operations center (SOC) systems enables automated prioritization of alerts and enrichment of security events using intelligence indicators.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] The drawback of automated analytics systems is that they can generate false positives or rely on low-quality indicators, which means analysts have to verify the results and provide a contextual interpretation.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] For this reason, many organizations adopt a hybrid model in which automated systems perform large-scale data processing while human analysts focus on interpretation, attribution, and strategic assessment of cyber threats.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attribution is the process of identifying who conducted a cyber attack: the individual actors, organized groups, or nation-state sponsors behind an intrusion.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] In threat intelligence, attribution helps organizations understand adversary intent, prioritize defenses, anticipate future targeting, and inform strategic decisions.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] It also supports law enforcement investigations and policy responses.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] However, attribution is inherently difficult and often remains probabilistic rather than definitive.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attackers routinely employ obfuscation techniques: using proxy infrastructure, VPNs, compromised intermediary systems, and stolen or leased tools.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Advanced threat actors deliberately plant false flags by mimicking the TTPs, language, or infrastructure patterns of other groups to misdirect attribution efforts.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] As a result, different threat intelligence vendors take varying approaches to attribution.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some explicitly attribute threat groups to specific nation-states or sponsoring organizations based on their analysis and confidence thresholds.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Others intentionally avoid geopolitical attribution, instead documenting only observable, undisputable facts, such as language artifacts in malware, shared infrastructure, or technical capabilities, and tracking adversary clusters by neutral designators.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attribution assessments are typically expressed with varying levels of confidence (low, medium, high) rather than certainty, and erroneous conclusions can have diplomatic, legal, or strategic consequences.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] In 2015 U.S. government legislation in the form of the Cybersecurity Information Sharing Act encouraged the sharing of CTI indicators between government and private organizations.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/cyber-threat-intelligence] In 2016, the U.S. government agency National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a publication (NIST SP 800–150) which further outlined the necessity for Cyber Threat Information Sharing as well as a framework for implementation.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Within international business, the **diamond model**, also known as **Porter's Diamond** or the **Porter Diamond Theory of National Advantage**, describes a nation's competitive advantage in the international market.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] In this model, four attributes are taken into consideration: factor conditions, demand conditions, related and supporting industries, and firm strategy, structure, and rivalry.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Strategic analysis typically focuses on two views of organization: the industry view and the resource-based view (RBV).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] These views analyse the organisation without taking into consideration relationship between the organizations strategic choice (i.e.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Porter generic strategies) and institutional frameworks.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] The diamond model is a tool for analyzing the organization's task environment.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] The diamond model highlights that strategic choices should not only be a function of industry structure and a firm's resources, it should also be a function of the constraints of the institutional framework.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Institutional analysis (such as the diamond model) becomes increasingly important as firms enter new operating environments and operate within new institutional frameworks.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Porter's National Diamond framework resulted from a study of patterns of comparative advantage among industrialized nations.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] It works to integrate much of Porter's previous work in his competitive five forces theory, his value chain framework as well as his theory of competitive advantage into a consolidated framework that looks at the sources of competitive advantage sourcable from the national context.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] It can be used both to analyze a firm's ability to function in a national market, as well as analyse a national market's ability to compete in an international market.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Two of the aforementioned pillars focus on the (national) macroeconomics environment to determine if the demand is present along with the factors needed for production (i.e. both extreme ends of the value chain).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Another pillar focuses on the specific relationships supporting industries have with the particular firm/nation/industry being studied.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] The last pillar it looks at the firm's strategic response (microeconomics) i.e. its strategy, taking into account the industry structure and rivalry (see five forces).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] In this way it tries to highlight areas of competitive advantage as well as competitive weakness, by looking at a companies/nations suitability to the particular conditions of a particular market.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Factor conditions include the nation's production resources, including infrastructure, labor force, land, and natural resources.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] According to Porter, "a nation does not inherit but instead creates the most important factors of production—such as skilled human resources or a scientific base".
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] For example, in analyzing Hollywood's preeminence in film production, Porter has pointed out the local concentration of skilled labor, including the different schools of film (UCLA and USC) in the area.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Also, resource constraints may encourage development of substitute capabilities; Japan's relative lack of raw materials has spurred miniaturization and zero-defect manufacturing.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] This component refers to industries that supply, distribute, or are otherwise related to the industry being examined.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] For many firms, the presence of related and supporting industries is of critical importance to the growth of that particular industry.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] A critical concept here is that national competitive strengths tend to be associated with "clusters" of industries.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] For example, Silicon Valley in the US and Silicon Glen in the UK are techno clusters of high-technology industries which includes individual computer software and semi-conductor firms.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] In Germany, a similar cluster exists around chemicals, synthetic dyes, textiles and textile machinery.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Demand conditions in the domestic market provide the primary driver of growth, innovation and quality improvement.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] The premise is that a strong domestic market stimulates the firm from being a startup to a slightly expanded and bigger organization.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] As an illustration, we can take the case of Germany which has some of the world's premier automobile companies like Mercedes, BMW, Porsche.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] German auto companies have dominated the world when it comes to the high-performance segment of the world automobile industry.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] However, their position in the market of cheaper, mass-produced autos is much weaker.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] This can be linked to a domestic market which has traditionally demanded a high level of engineering performance.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Also, the transport infrastructure of Germany, with its Autobahns does tend to favor high-performance automobiles.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] National performance in particular sectors is inevitably related to the strategies and the structure of the firms in that sector.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Competition plays a big role in driving innovation and the subsequent upgradation of competitive advantage.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Since domestic competition is more direct and impacts earlier than steps taken by foreign competitors, the stimulus provided by them is higher in terms of innovation and efficiency.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] As an example, the Japanese automobile industry with 8 major competitors (Honda, Toyota, Suzuki, Isuzu, Nissan, Mazda, Mitsubishi, and Subaru) provide intense competition in the domestic market, as well as the foreign markets in which they compete.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Porter identifies two other variables that affect competitiveness.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] The role of government in Porter's Diamond Model is "acting as a catalyst and challenger; it is to encourage - or even push - companies to raise their aspirations and move to higher levels of competitive performance ..." .
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] They must encourage companies to raise their performance, stimulate early demand for advanced products, focus on specialized factor creation and to stimulate local rivalry by limiting direct cooperation and enforcing anti-trust regulations.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] The role of chance basically denotes the idea that it may occur that many times a product or an enterprise may get an opportunity to maximize its benefits out of sheer luck.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Thus chance plays a key role in determining the fate of the product as well.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Criticisms of Porter's national diamond model revolve around a number of assumptions that underlie it.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/diamond-model] Porter generalized from the North American, European and Japanese experiences; for countries developing in the presence of these now developed regions of the world, the model may need to be re-examined.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/indicator-of-compromise] An **indicator of compromise** (**IoC**) in computer forensics is an artifact observed on a computer network or within an operating system that, with high confidence, indicates a computer intrusion.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/indicator-of-compromise] Common IoCs include virus signatures, suspicious IP addresses, MD5 hashes of malware files, and malicious URLs or domain names associated with botnet command-and-control servers.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/indicator-of-compromise] Once IoCs are identified through incident response or forensic analysis, they can be used for early detection of future attacks with intrusion detection systems and antivirus software.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/indicator-of-compromise] Known indicators are often exchanged within the cybersecurity industry, commonly using the Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) to indicate how information may be shared.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/indicator-of-compromise] Other frameworks and standards are also used to support secure information sharing.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The STIX fonts are available as fully hinted OpenType/CFF fonts.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The project was initiated in 1995 and officially released its first stable version (STIX 1.0) in May 2010, after 15 years of development, with subsequent updates including STIX Two released in 2016.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] There is currently no TrueType version of the STIX fonts available, but the STIX Mission Statement includes the intention to create one in the future.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] However, there exists an unofficial conversion of STIX Fonts (from the beta version release) to TrueType, suitable for use with software without OpenType support.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] STIX fonts also include natural language glyphs for Latin, Greek and Cyrillic.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The family is designed to be visually compatible with the Times New Roman family, a popular choice in book publishing.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] Among the glyphs in STIX, 32.9% have been contributed by the project members.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The commercial TeX vendor and TeX font foundry MicroPress has been contracted to create the additional glyphs.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The STIX project will also create a TeX implementation.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] Goals also include incorporating the characters into Unicode, and ensuring that browsers can use them.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] Members of the STIX Fonts project, known collectively as the STI Pub consortium, include the American Institute of Physics, the American Chemical Society, the American Mathematical Society, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, the American Physical Society, and Elsevier.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] A beta version of the fonts was released on October 31, 2007.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] This version does not include enough of the OpenType mathematical layout features present in Cambria Math, so it is not usable to the fullest extent in Microsoft Office 2007.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The Latin glyph set included in the beta version does not yet cover all the characters required to typeset in Eastern European languages.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] "Final design changes" were declared "complete" at the project website on June 9, 2008.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] A release by end of May 2009 for the "initial production release" was announced, still without the support for OpenType layout features of Office 2007 or TeX.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] In September 2009, the fonts went to the final packaging stage.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] However, in October, missing glyphs were discovered, adding a delay.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The fonts were scheduled to be released in April 2010, and released on May 28, 2010.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The project has taken considerably longer than forecast.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The website has been updated only intermittently, and thus has regularly been out-of-date, with forecast milestones often being overshot.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] This version facilitates equation editing in recent versions of Microsoft Word.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] Version 1.1.0 with LaTeX support was released on May 29, 2013.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] On December 1, 2016, the official project website announced the release of STIX version 2.0.0.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] This was created by Ross Mills and John Hudson of Tiro Typeworks.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] Unlike the previous version, which closely matches Nimbus Roman No.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] 9 L, it is an original design loosely inspired by a smaller 10 point size of Times New Roman, with a higher x-height.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] In April 2018, the Type 1 version of the STIX Two fonts for use in LaTeX was released.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] At the same time, the STIX project hosting platform has been migrated to GitHub (https://github.com/stipub/stixfonts/).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The STIX Fonts are included in OS X in versions from Lion (10.7) onwards.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The JavaScript framework MathJax uses the STIX fonts for including mathematics in web pages.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] Installing the fonts on the local computer improves MathJax's typesetting speed.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] The Math Editor equation editor uses STIX fonts as its primary font.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] A precursor to the STIX project is the ESSTIX (Elsevier Science STIX) font, developed and later donated by Elsevier.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] It is currently available from the World Wide Web Consortium as part of the Amaya (web browser).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/stix] However, the STIX fonts are not used in most of the peer-reviewed journals published by Elsevier.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] In computer security, a **threat** is a potential negative action or event enabled by a vulnerability that results in an unwanted impact to a computer system or application.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] A threat can be either a negative "intentional" event like hacking or an "accidental" negative event or otherwise a circumstance, capability, action, or event (incident is often used as a blanket term).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] A *threat actor* who is an individual or group that can perform the threat action, such as exploiting a vulnerability to actualise a negative impact.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] An *exploit* is a vulnerability that a threat actor used to cause an incident.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] A resource (both physical or logical) can have one or more vulnerabilities that can be exploited by a threat agent in a threat action.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The result can potentially compromise the confidentiality, integrity or availability properties of resources (potentially different than the vulnerable one) of the organization and others involved parties (customers, suppliers).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The so-called CIA triad is the basis of information security.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The attack can be *active* when it attempts to alter system resources or affect their operation: so it compromises Integrity or Availability.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] A "*passive attack*" attempts to learn or make use of information from the system but does not affect system resources: so it compromises Confidentiality.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] OWASP (see figure) depicts the same phenomenon in slightly different terms: a threat agent through an attack vector exploits a weakness (vulnerability) of the system and the related security controls causing a technical impact on an IT resource (asset) connected to a business impact.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Countermeasures are also called security controls; when applied to the transmission of information are named security services.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The overall picture represents the risk factors of the risk scenario.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The widespread of computer dependencies and the consequent raising of the consequence of a successful attack, led to a new term cyberwarfare.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Nowadays the many real attacks exploit Psychology at least as much as technology.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Phishing and Pretexting and other methods are called social engineering techniques.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The Web 2.0 applications, specifically Social network services, can be a mean to get in touch with people in charge of system administration or even system security, inducing them to reveal sensitive information.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Note that a threat type can have multiple origins.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Recent trends in computer threats show an increase in ransomware attacks, supply chain attacks, and fileless malware.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Ransomware attacks involve the encryption of a victim's files and a demand for payment to restore access.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Supply chain attacks target the weakest links in a supply chain to gain access to high-value targets.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Fileless malware attacks use techniques that allow malware to run in memory, making it difficult to detect.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Microsoft previously rated the risk of security threats using five categories in a classification called DREAD: Risk assessment model.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The spread over a network of threats can lead to dangerous situations.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] In military and civil fields, threat level has been defined: for example INFOCON is a threat level used by the US.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Leading antivirus software vendors publish global threat level on their websites.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] In cybersecurity and risk assessment, a threat actor (or *threat agents*, *attackers*, or *adversaries*) is a person, group, organisation, state, or other entity with the ability to cause, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Threat actors are commonly analysed according to their motivations, resources, technical capability, access to systems, relationship to a target, and degree of connection to state authority.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] They may exploit vulnerabilities, conduct social engineering, steal or monetise data, disrupt operations, or support other actors who carry out such activity.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Because the term covers a wide range of actors, researchers and security organisations use taxonomies that distinguish between groups such as cybercriminals, state-linked actors, ideologically motivated actors, thrill seekers or trolls, insiders, and competitors.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Threat actor classifications are used in risk management, cyber threat intelligence, and incident response to connect observed behaviour with possible objectives and likely future activity.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The categories are not always mutually exclusive: the same actor may combine criminal, ideological, commercial, or state-linked motivations, and different organisations may use different names for similar actors.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] A collection of threats in a particular domain or context, with information on identified vulnerable assets, threats, risks, threat actors and observed trends.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Threats should be managed by operating an ISMS, performing all the IT risk management activities foreseen by laws, standards and methodologies.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Very large organizations tend to adopt business continuity management plans in order to protect, maintain and recover business-critical processes and systems.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Some of these plans are implemented by computer security incident response team (CSIRT).
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Threat management must identify, evaluate, and categorize threats.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Many organizations perform only a subset of these methods, adopting countermeasures based on a non-systematic approach, resulting in *computer insecurity*.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Information security awareness is a significant market.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] There has been a lot of software developed to deal with IT threats, including both open-source software and proprietary software.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Threat management involves a wide variety of threats including physical threats like flood and fire.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] While ISMS risk assessment process does incorporate threat management for cyber threats such as remote buffer overflows the risk assessment process doesn't include processes such as threat intelligence management or response procedures.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] Cyber threat management (CTM) is emerging as the best practice for managing cyber threats beyond the basic risk assessment found in ISMS.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] It enables early identification of threats, data-driven situational awareness, accurate decision-making, and timely threat mitigating actions.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] The SANS Institute has conducted research and surveys on the effectiveness of threat hunting to track and disrupt cyber adversaries as early in their process as possible.
[src:diamond-model-intrusion/threat-computer-security] According to a survey performed in 2019, "61% [of the respondents] report at least an 11% measurable improvement in their overall security posture" and 23.6% of the respondents have experienced a 'significant improvement' in reducing the dwell time.
